  ## [**Understanding color theory**](https://www.figma.com/resource-library/color-combinations/\#understanding-color-theory)
  
  Understanding [color theory](https://www.figma.com/resource-library/what-is-color-theory/) is the key to creating impactful color combinations in UI design. The tools below help create color combinations with a specific purpose, evoke certain emotions, and improve the user experience.
  
  ### [**Color wheel**](https://www.figma.com/resource-library/color-combinations/\#color-wheel)
  
  The [color wheel](https://www.figma.com/color-wheel/) is the core of color theory, organizing colors based on relationships. It includes three main color types: [primary](https://www.figma.com/resource-library/what-are-primary-colors/) (red, yellow, and [blue](https://www.figma.com/colors/blue/)), [secondary](https://www.figma.com/resource-library/what-are-secondary-colors/) ( [green](https://www.figma.com/colors/green/), [orange](https://www.figma.com/colors/orange/), and [violet](https://www.figma.com/colors/violet/)), and tertiary (a mix of primary and secondary colors). Colors naturally complement one another based on their position on the color wheel.
  
  ### [**Color harmony**](https://www.figma.com/resource-library/color-combinations/\#color-harmony)
  
  Color harmony refers to how colors are arranged to create a visually pleasing design. It’s a technique that ensures colors in a palette work well together. A harmonious color combination looks good and also:
  
  - Impacts the user experience by making designs more appealing and easier to navigate
  - Establishes [visual hierarchy](https://www.figma.com/resource-library/what-is-visual-hierarchy/), guiding users’ attention to key elements and content
  - Contributes to brand recognition through consistent and complementary color choices
  - Evokes a specific mood and tone, creating the desired emotional response from users
  - Ensures the [accessibility of a design](https://www.figma.com/resource-library/creating-accessible-and-inclusive-design/) by adhering to color contrast guidelines, making content readable for all users
  
  ### [**Color properties**](https://www.figma.com/resource-library/color-combinations/\#color-properties)
  
  Color properties also play a significant role in color theory and how users perceive and interact with colors. Experimenting with hues, value, saturation, and temperature can change a color’s appearance and even wholly change its effects on the [human brain](https://www.nih.gov/news-events/news-releases/envision-color-activity-patterns-brain-are-specific-color-you-see).
  
  For example, you can use the bold, attention-grabbing nature of the [color yellow](https://www.figma.com/colors/yellow/) to make essential UI elements stand out. But when you change its value and add a white tint to create [pastel yellow](https://www.figma.com/colors/pastel-yellow/), it softens the shade and brings a tranquiland freshfeeling to designs.
  
  ### [**Color psychology**](https://www.figma.com/resource-library/color-combinations/\#color-psychology)
  
  Color psychology explores the emotional and psychological associations with different colors. Colors and their many hues can influence a user’s mood, behavior, and perception.
  
  For instance, dark blue evokes a sense of tranquility and reliability, and maroon has qualities that ignite feelings of confidence and stability. Referencing color psychology when building color combinations ensures you elicit the right response within designs.
  
  ## [**Types of color combinations**](https://www.figma.com/resource-library/color-combinations/\#types-of-color-combinations)
  
  You can use many color combinations to evoke emotions and create visually engaging designs. Some of the most common ones include:
  
  - **[Complementary](https://www.figma.com/resource-library/what-are-complementary-colors/).** These colors are located on opposite ends of the color wheel, creating a striking contrast when paired.
  - **[Monochromatic](https://www.figma.com/resource-library/monochromatic-colors/).** These shades include a lighter or darker version of the base color to create a consistent and subtle color palette.
  - **Analogous.** These hues are closely related and sit next to each other on the color wheel to create a natural [color scheme](https://www.figma.com/resource-library/website-color-schemes/).
  - **[Triadic](https://www.figma.com/resource-library/what-are-triadic-colors/).** This combination includes three colors equally distributed around the color wheel, one used as the primary color and the others as accent shades. These types of color palettes create vibrant and eye-catching designs.
  - **Tetradic.** This color combination includes four colors that form a square on the color wheel and are equal distances apart. Tetradic color schemes are more complex and tricky to balance, but create a vivid contrast.
  - **[Split complementary](https://www.figma.com/resource-library/what-are-split-complementary-colors/).** This color combination includes a base color and the two colors on either side of its direct complementary color on the color wheel. This creates a vibrant yet balanced color scheme.
  
  ## [**Color combination examples**](https://www.figma.com/resource-library/color-combinations/\#color-combination-examples)
  
  Here are a few examples of tech companies strategically using color palettes to evoke emotion and convey their core values.
  
